===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|たちばな}}
{{wp|ja:タチバナ}}
{{wp|Citrus tachibana}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=たちはな|橘|tr=tatibana}}.  First cited in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2}}</ref>

According to the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' in a section describing the 90th year of the reign of the legendary {{m|ja||{{w|lang=ja|垂仁天皇}}|tr=Suinin Tennō|{{w|Emperor Suinin}}|pos=traditionally regarded as living from 69 BCE – 70 CE and reigning from 29 BCE – 70 CE}}, a legendary figure named {{m|ja||{{w|lang=ja|田道間守}}|tr={{w|Tajimamori}}}} was tasked with bringing back from the heavens a {{m|ja||非時香菓|tr=tokijiku no kagu no konomi|pos=literally, “timeless fragrant tree-fruit”;  the same incident is also included in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}''}}.  This is often interpreted to be a reference to ''tachibana'', but the text itself is not specific.<ref name="KDJ2"/>

A surface analysis suggests that this is a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=たちばな|立ち|tr1=tachi|t1=[[standing]]|pos1=from verb {{m|ja|立つ|tr=tatsu||to [[stand]]}}|花|tr2=hana|t2=[[flower]]}}.

Shortened to ''tachi'' for some compounds.

